Note:
Haskell Lexer - Complete tokenization for Haskell language

This file provides comprehensive lexical analysis for the Haskell programming
language, including all keywords, operators, literals, identifiers, and
special syntax for pure functional programming constructs.

Haskell Features Covered:
- Keywords (data, type, class, instance, where, let, in, case, of, if, then, else, etc.)
- Operators (function application, composition, arithmetic, logical, etc.)
- Identifiers (variables, constructors, modules, qualified names)
- Literals (integers, floats, characters, strings, list comprehensions)
- Special syntax (layout-sensitive parsing, lambda expressions, type signatures)
- Comments (single-line and multi-line)
- Indentation and layout rules
- Type constructors and type variables
- Pattern matching syntax
- Module system (imports, exports, qualified names)

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Keywords
Constant TOKEN_DATA as Integer is 1001        Note: data
Constant TOKEN_TYPE as Integer is 1002        Note: type
Constant TOKEN_NEWTYPE as Integer is 1003     Note: newtype
Constant TOKEN_CLASS as Integer is 1004       Note: class
Constant TOKEN_INSTANCE as Integer is 1005    Note: instance
Constant TOKEN_WHERE as Integer is 1006       Note: where
Constant TOKEN_LET as Integer is 1007         Note: let
Constant TOKEN_IN as Integer is 1008          Note: in
Constant TOKEN_CASE as Integer is 1009        Note: case
Constant TOKEN_OF as Integer is 1010          Note: of
Constant TOKEN_IF as Integer is 1011          Note: if
Constant TOKEN_THEN as Integer is 1012        Note: then
Constant TOKEN_ELSE as Integer is 1013        Note: else
Constant TOKEN_MODULE as Integer is 1014      Note: module
Constant TOKEN_IMPORT as Integer is 1015      Note: import
Constant TOKEN_QUALIFIED as Integer is 1016   Note: qualified
Constant TOKEN_AS as Integer is 1017          Note: as
Constant TOKEN_HIDING as Integer is 1018      Note: hiding
Constant TOKEN_INFIX as Integer is 1019       Note: infix
Constant TOKEN_INFIXL as Integer is 1020      Note: infixl
Constant TOKEN_INFIXR as Integer is 1021      Note: infixr
Constant TOKEN_DERIVING as Integer is 1022    Note: deriving
Constant TOKEN_DO as Integer is 1023          Note: do
Constant TOKEN_FOREIGN as Integer is 1024     Note: foreign

Note: Operators and Special Symbols
Constant TOKEN_ARROW as Integer is 2001       Note: ->
Constant TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW as Integer is 2002 Note: =>
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_ARROW as Integer is 2003  Note: <-
Constant TOKEN_LAMBDA as Integer is 2004      Note: \
Constant TOKEN_PIPE as Integer is 2005        Note: |
Constant TOKEN_AT as Integer is 2006          Note: @
Constant TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON as Integer is 2007 Note: ::
Constant TOKEN_DOT as Integer is 2008         Note: .
Constant TOKEN_DOUBLE_DOT as Integer is 2009  Note: ..
Constant TOKEN_DOLLAR as Integer is 2010      Note: $
Constant TOKEN_COMPOSE as Integer is 2011     Note: composition operator
Constant TOKEN_BIND as Integer is 2012        Note: >>=
Constant TOKEN_SEQUENCE as Integer is 2013    Note: >>
Constant TOKEN_APPLICATIVE as Integer is 2014 Note: <*>
Constant TOKEN_FUNCTOR as Integer is 2015     Note: <$>
Constant TOKEN_ALTERNATIVE as Integer is 2016 Note: <|>

Note: Arithmetic and Comparison Operators
Constant TOKEN_PLUS as Integer is 2101        Note: +
Constant TOKEN_MINUS as Integer is 2102       Note: -
Constant TOKEN_MULTIPLY as Integer is 2103    Note: *
Constant TOKEN_DIVIDE as Integer is 2104      Note: /
Constant TOKEN_POWER as Integer is 2105       Note: **
Constant TOKEN_POWER_INT as Integer is 2106   Note: ^
Constant TOKEN_POWER_NEG as Integer is 2107   Note: ^^
Constant TOKEN_MOD as Integer is 2108         Note: mod
Constant TOKEN_DIV as Integer is 2109         Note: div
Constant TOKEN_QUOT as Integer is 2110        Note: quot
Constant TOKEN_REM as Integer is 2111         Note: rem

Constant TOKEN_EQUAL as Integer is 2201       Note: ==
Constant TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL as Integer is 2202   Note: /=
Constant TOKEN_LESS_THAN as Integer is 2203   Note: <
Constant TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL as Integer is 2204  Note: <=
Constant TOKEN_GREATER_THAN as Integer is 2205 Note: >
Constant TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL as Integer is 2206 Note: >=

Note: Logical Operators
Constant TOKEN_AND as Integer is 2301         Note: &&
Constant TOKEN_OR as Integer is 2302          Note: ||
Constant TOKEN_NOT as Integer is 2303         Note: not

Note: List Operators
Constant TOKEN_CONS as Integer is 2401        Note: :
Constant TOKEN_APPEND as Integer is 2402      Note: ++
Constant TOKEN_LIST_MINUS as Integer is 2403  Note: \\

Note: Delimiters
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN as Integer is 3001  Note: (
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN as Integer is 3002 Note: )
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET as Integer is 3003 Note: [
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET as Integer is 3004 Note: ]
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE as Integer is 3005  Note: {
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE as Integer is 3006 Note: }
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 3007       Note: ,
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 3008   Note: ;
Constant TOKEN_UNDERSCORE as Integer is 3009  Note: _

Note: Literals
Constant TOKEN_INTEGER as Integer is 4001     Note: Integer literal
Constant TOKEN_FLOAT as Integer is 4002       Note: Float literal
Constant TOKEN_CHAR as Integer is 4003        Note: Character literal
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 4004      Note: String literal

Note: Identifiers
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 5001  Note: Variable identifier
Constant TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR as Integer is 5002 Note: Constructor identifier
Constant TOKEN_OPERATOR as Integer is 5003    Note: Custom operator
Constant TOKEN_MODULE_NAME as Integer is 5004 Note: Module name
Constant TOKEN_QUALIFIED as Integer is 5005   Note: Qualified identifier

Note: Layout and Structure
Constant TOKEN_LAYOUT_START as Integer is 6001 Note: Virtual {
Constant TOKEN_LAYOUT_END as Integer is 6002   Note: Virtual }
Constant TOKEN_LAYOUT_SEP as Integer is 6003   Note: Virtual ;
Constant TOKEN_NEWLINE as Integer is 6004      Note: Significant newline
Constant TOKEN_INDENT as Integer is 6005       Note: Indentation level

Note: Special
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 9001         Note: End of file
Constant TOKEN_UNKNOWN as Integer is 9002     Note: Unknown token

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "HaskellLexer":
    source as Integer              Note: Source code string
    position as Integer            Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer                Note: Current line number
    column as Integer              Note: Current column number
    length as Integer              Note: Length of source string
    current_char as Integer        Note: Current character
    layout_stack as Integer        Note: Stack for layout/indentation
    in_string as Integer           Note: String parsing state
    in_comment as Integer          Note: Comment parsing state
End Type

Type called "HaskellToken":
    type as Integer               Note: Token type constant
    value as Integer              Note: Token value (string)
    line as Integer               Note: Line number
    column as Integer             Note: Column number
    length as Integer             Note: Token length
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_haskell_lexer" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Haskell lexer for source code

    @Reasoning:
    Initializes a new Haskell lexer with the given source code. Sets up
    initial position, line/column tracking, and layout stack for Haskell's
    indentation-sensitive parsing.
    @End Reasoning

    Let lexer_size be 56  Note: 7 fields × 8 bytes each
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0     Note: position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 1    Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1    Note: column

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, source_length

    Note: Get first character
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source_code, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, first_char

    Note: Initialize layout stack for Haskell's layout-sensitive syntax
    Note: Stack tracks indentation levels for implicit braces/semicolons
    Let layout_stack be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, layout_stack

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 0    Note: in_string
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, 0    Note: in_comment

    Return lexer
End Process

Process called "destroy_haskell_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Haskell lexer and free memory

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        Note: Free layout stack if allocated
        Let layout_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
        If layout_stack is not equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with layout_stack
        End If

        proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "create_haskell_token" takes token_type as Integer, value as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Haskell token

    @Reasoning:
    Creates a token structure containing type, value, and position information.
    Essential for parser to understand token sequence and provide error messages
    with accurate location information.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_size be 40  Note: 5 fields × 8 bytes each
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column

    Let value_length be 0
    If value is not equal to 0:
        Set value_length to proc string_length from StringCore with value
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, value_length

    Return token
End Process

Process called "destroy_haskell_token" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Haskell token and free memory

    If token is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with token
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "advance_haskell_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance lexer to next character

    @Reasoning:
    Moves lexer forward one character, updating position, line, and column
    counters. Handles newline detection for proper line tracking.
    @End Reasoning

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Check for newline
    If current_char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
        Set line to line plus 1
        Set column to 1
    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Set current_char to 0 minus 1  Note: EOF
    Otherwise:
        Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
        Set current_char to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, current_char

    Return current_char
End Process

Process called "peek_haskell_lexer" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at character at offset from current position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0 minus 1  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, peek_pos
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_haskell_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65 and char is less than or equal to 90:
        Return 1  Note: A-Z
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97 and char is less than or equal to 122:
        Return 1  Note: a-z
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_haskell_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is numeric

    If char is greater than or equal to 48 and char is less than or equal to 57:
        Return 1  Note: 0-9
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_haskell_alphanum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let is_alpha be proc is_haskell_alpha from char
    Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit from char

    If is_alpha is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If is_digit is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_haskell_operator_char" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character can be part of operator

    @Reasoning:
    Haskell allows custom operators composed of specific symbol characters.
    This function identifies all valid operator characters according to
    Haskell language specification.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Standard operator characters
    If char is equal to 33:   Return 1  Note: !
    If char is equal to 35:   Return 1  Note: #
    If char is equal to 36:   Return 1  Note: $
    If char is equal to 37:   Return 1  Note: %
    If char is equal to 38:   Return 1  Note: &
    If char is equal to 42:   Return 1  Note: *
    If char is equal to 43:   Return 1  Note: +
    If char is equal to 45:   Return 1  Note: -
    If char is equal to 46:   Return 1  Note: .
    If char is equal to 47:   Return 1  Note: /
    If char is equal to 60:   Return 1  Note: <
    If char is equal to 61:   Return 1  Note: =
    If char is equal to 62:   Return 1  Note: >
    If char is equal to 63:   Return 1  Note: ?
    If char is equal to 64:   Return 1  Note: @
    If char is equal to 92:   Return 1  Note: \
    If char is equal to 94:   Return 1  Note: ^
    If char is equal to 124:  Return 1  Note: |
    If char is equal to 126:  Return 1  Note: ~

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_haskell_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:   Return 1  Note: space
    If char is equal to 9:    Return 1  Note: tab
    If char is equal to 10:   Return 1  Note: newline
    If char is equal to 13:   Return 1  Note: carriage return

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "recognize_haskell_keyword" takes word as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recognize Haskell keywords and return appropriate token type

    @Reasoning:
    Checks if given word matches any Haskell keyword. Returns specific token
    type for keywords, or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for non-keywords. Essential for
    distinguishing reserved words from user-defined identifiers.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Core language keywords
    Let data_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "data"
    Let match be proc string_equals from StringCore with word, data_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with data_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DATA
    End If

    Let type_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, type_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with type_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_TYPE
    End If

    Let newtype_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "newtype"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, newtype_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with newtype_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NEWTYPE
    End If

    Let class_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "class"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, class_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with class_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CLASS
    End If

    Let instance_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "instance"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, instance_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with instance_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INSTANCE
    End If

    Let where_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "where"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, where_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with where_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WHERE
    End If

    Let let_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "let"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, let_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with let_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_LET
    End If

    Let in_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "in"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, in_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with in_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IN
    End If

    Let case_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "case"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, case_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with case_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CASE
    End If

    Let of_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "of"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, of_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with of_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_OF
    End If

    Let if_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "if"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, if_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with if_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If

    Let then_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "then"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, then_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with then_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_THEN
    End If

    Let else_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "else"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, else_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with else_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If

    Note: Module system keywords
    Let module_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "module"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, module_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with module_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_MODULE
    End If

    Let import_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "import"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, import_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with import_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IMPORT
    End If

    Let qualified_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "qualified"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, qualified_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with qualified_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_QUALIFIED
    End If

    Let as_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "as"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, as_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with as_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_AS
    End If

    Let hiding_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "hiding"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, hiding_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with hiding_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_HIDING
    End If

    Note: Operator fixity keywords
    Let infix_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "infix"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, infix_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with infix_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INFIX
    End If

    Let infixl_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "infixl"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, infixl_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with infixl_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INFIXL
    End If

    Let infixr_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "infixr"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, infixr_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with infixr_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INFIXR
    End If

    Let deriving_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "deriving"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, deriving_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with deriving_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DERIVING
    End If

    Let do_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "do"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, do_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with do_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DO
    End If

    Let foreign_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "foreign"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, foreign_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with foreign_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FOREIGN
    End If

    Note: Not a keyword - return identifier
    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanning Functions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "scan_haskell_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan Haskell identifier or keyword

    @Reasoning:
    Scans alphanumeric identifiers, handling both lowercase variables and
    uppercase constructors. Checks for keywords after scanning complete
    identifier. Supports apostrophe and underscore in identifiers.
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Scan identifier characters
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_alnum be proc is_haskell_alphanum from current_char
        If is_alnum is equal to 0:
            If current_char is not equal to 95:      Note: _
                If current_char is not equal to 39:  Note: '
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let identifier_length be end_pos minus start_pos
    Let identifier be proc substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, identifier_length

    Note: Check if it's a keyword
    Let token_type be proc recognize_haskell_keyword from identifier

    Note: Check if it's a constructor (starts with uppercase)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with identifier, 0
        If first_char is greater than or equal to 65 and first_char is less than or equal to 90:
            Set token_type to TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR
        End If
    End If

    Return identifier
End Process

Process called "scan_haskell_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan numeric literal (integer or float)

    @Reasoning:
    Handles various Haskell numeric formats including decimal, hexadecimal,
    octal, binary, and floating point numbers. Supports scientific notation
    and proper type inference.
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let is_float be 0

    Note: Check for hex/octal/binary prefix
    If current_char is equal to 48:  Note: 0
        Let next_char be proc peek_haskell_lexer from lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 120 or next_char is equal to 88:  Note: x or X (hex)
            proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer  Note: Skip 0
            proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer  Note: Skip x
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            Note: Scan hex digits
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let is_hex_digit be 0
                If current_char is greater than or equal to 48 and current_char is less than or equal to 57:
                    Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: 0-9
                End If
                If current_char is greater than or equal to 65 and current_char is less than or equal to 70:
                    Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: A-F
                End If
                If current_char is greater than or equal to 97 and current_char is less than or equal to 102:
                    Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: a-f
                End If

                If is_hex_digit is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            End While
        End If

        If next_char is equal to 111 or next_char is equal to 79:  Note: o or O (octal)
            proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer  Note: Skip 0
            proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer  Note: Skip o
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            Note: Scan octal digits
            While current_char is greater than or equal to 48 and current_char is less than or equal to 55:
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Scan decimal digits
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit from current_char
        If is_digit is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
    End While

    Note: Check for decimal point
    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Let next_char be proc peek_haskell_lexer from lexer, 1
        Let next_is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit from next_char

        If next_is_digit is equal to 1:
            Set is_float to 1
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer  Note: Skip .

            Note: Scan fractional part
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit from current_char
                If is_digit is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for exponent
    If current_char is equal to 101 or current_char is equal to 69:  Note: e or E
        Set is_float to 1
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer

        Note: Optional sign
        If current_char is equal to 43 or current_char is equal to 45:  Note: plus or -
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        End If

        Note: Scan exponent digits
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit from current_char
            If is_digit is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        End While
    End If

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let number_length be end_pos minus start_pos
    Let number_str be proc substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, number_length

    Return number_str
End Process

Process called "scan_haskell_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal with escape sequences

    @Reasoning:
    Handles Haskell string literals with full escape sequence support,
    including Unicode escapes, control characters, and gap elimination.
    Proper handling of multi-line strings and string gaps.
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    Note: Scan string content
    While current_char is not equal to 34:  Note: "
        If current_char is equal to 0 minus 1:  Note: EOF
            Note: Unterminated string
            Return 0
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 92:  Note: \
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer

            Note: Handle escape sequences
            If current_char is equal to 110:      Note: \n
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 116:  Note: \t
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 114:  Note: \r
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 98:   Note: \b
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 102:  Note: \f
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 118:  Note: \v
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 97:   Note: \a
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 92:   Note: \\
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 34:   Note: \"
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 39:   Note: \'
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
            Otherwise:
                Note: Handle numeric escape sequences and Unicode
                Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit from current_char
                If is_digit is equal to 1:
                    Note: Decimal escape sequence
                    While 1 is equal to 1:
                        Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit from current_char
                        If is_digit is equal to 0:
                            Break
                        End If
                        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
                    End While
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Unknown escape - consume character
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
                End If
            Otherwise:
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        End If
    End While

    Note: Skip closing quote
    proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let string_length be end_pos minus start_pos minus 2  Note: Exclude quotes
    Let string_content_start be start_pos plus 1  Note: Skip opening quote
    Let string_str be proc substring from StringCore with source, string_content_start, string_length

    Return string_str
End Process

Process called "scan_haskell_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan character literal

    @Reasoning:
    Handles single character literals including escape sequences.
    Supports all Haskell escape sequences and Unicode characters.
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    Note: Handle escape sequences
    If current_char is equal to 92:  Note: \
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer

        Note: Process escape sequence (same as string but for single char)
        If current_char is equal to 110:      Note: \n
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 116:  Note: \t
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 114:  Note: \r
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 92:   Note: \\
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        Otherwise: If current_char is equal to 39:   Note: \'
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        Otherwise:
            Note: Other escape sequences
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
        Otherwise:
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer
    End If

    Note: Expect closing quote
    If current_char is not equal to 39:  Note: '
        Note: Invalid character literal
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Skip closing quote
    proc advance_haskell_lexer from lexer

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let char_length be end_pos minus start_pos minus 2  Note: Exclude quotes
    Let char_content_start be start_pos plus 1
    Let char_str be proc substring from StringCore with source, char_content_start, char_length

    Return char_str
End Process

Process called "scan_haskell_operator" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan custom operator sequence

    @Reasoning:
    Scans custom operators composed of operator symbols. Handles multi-character
    operators and distinguishes them from individual symbols.
